<TITLE> 502 centres to update voter database </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 24 (bdnews24.com) - The Election Commission will set up 502 electoral database server stations countrywide to regularly update and maintain the voter roll, the chief election commissioner said Tuesday. A Tk 206.70 crore project on 'Construction of Server Stations for the Electoral Database' that will set up centres in all upazilas and urban areas, ATM Shamsul Huda said. Two development partners -- DFID and Netherlands -- will provide Tk 96.10 crore of the total cost of the project, while the government will provide Tk 110.60 crore, tentatively scheduled to be completed by Oct. 2010. The Netherlands government and the UNDP signed an agreement Tuesday in presence of the CEC at the Election Commission Secretariat for the implementation of the new project. Bea ten Tusscher, Netherlands ambassador and Stefan Priesner, UNDP country director signed the agreement on behalf of their respective sides. Talking to the reporters, the CEC said the construction works in all 481 upazilas and in urban areas would simultaneously start in mid-April. He said the public works department and the local government department would implement the constructions respectively in urban and rural areas. "This project will strengthen the independence of the Election Commission and enable the public to enquire about voter registration and other electoral matters at the local level," said Stefan Priesner. The Netherlands ambassador said, "We hope that this partnership will sustain the efforts for democratisation in Bangladesh and further strengthen its political process." 
